## Part 2 — Phase 2: Web application discovery

**Global internal gotchas** (apply to every tool below):

- **Self-signed / internal-CA TLS:** every tool needs `-k` / `--insecure` / `tls_verify=false`, OR drop the corp root CA into the trust store (preferred).
- **NTLM / Kerberos / SSO:** pure CLI fuzzers can't negotiate NTLM. Three patterns: (1) snatch a cookie from an authenticated Burp session and pass with `-b`/`Cookie:`, (2) front-end the tool through cntlm/Burp and target `http://127.0.0.1:3128`, or (3) grab a Bearer/JWT and inject with `-H`.
- **Update checks break offline runs** — set `-duc`/`-disable-update-check` everywhere.
- **Fragile infra** — internal apps rarely have WAFs but routinely have 2-core VMs and single-replica DBs. Cap threads (`-t 20`, not 200), add `--delay`/`-rl`, watch for blanket 500s = you're DoSing the app.

### 2.1 httpx — probe live services

```bash
httpx -l ips.txt \
      -ports 80,443,8080,8443,8000,8888,9000,9090,3000,5000,7001,7002,8081,8180,9443 \
      -title -tech-detect -status-code -favicon -tls-grab -jarm \
      -web-server -location -ip -cname -no-fallback \
      -threads 50 -rate-limit 150 -timeout 10 -duc -silent \
      -o live.txt -json -srd responses/

# Pin internal resolvers
httpx -l ips.txt -r 10.10.0.53:53,10.10.0.54:53 -title -sc -duc
```

`-no-fallback` keeps both http:// and https:// results (internal apps often serve plaintext :8080 AND TLS :8443 for the same app). `-tech-detect` uses bundled wappalyzergo data — local, offline. `-favicon` emits mmh3 hashes that you cross-reference against an offline lookup table.

### 2.2 Screenshot sweep — gowitness / eyewitness

A /16 can yield 200+ web interfaces; visual triage in gallery view is 10× faster than clicking.

```bash
gowitness scan file -f live.txt --write-db --chrome-path /usr/bin/chromium \
    --screenshot-path ./screens -t 10 --timeout 30
gowitness report serve --address 127.0.0.1:7171    # then browse localhost:7171

# Chrome through Burp for authenticated screenshots
gowitness scan file -f live.txt --chrome-proxy http://127.0.0.1:8080 \
    --chrome-header "Cookie: session=..."

# EyeWitness (Python) — legacy-friendly, categorized HTML report
eyewitness --web -f live.txt -d eyewitness-report --no-prompt --timeout 30 --threads 10
```

`--chrome-path /usr/bin/chromium` is essential on locked-down jumpboxes that can't pull Chromium from Google CDN.

### 2.3 Fingerprinting — whatweb, webanalyze

```bash
# whatweb — 1800+ plugins, fully offline; aggressive -a 3 is very strong on legacy stacks
whatweb -a 3 --no-errors --log-json=ww.json -i live.txt

# webanalyze (Go — maintained Wappalyzer port since npm Wappalyzer CLI was archived)
webanalyze -update       # on staging — grabs technologies.json
webanalyze -hosts live.txt -crawl 1 -worker 4 -output json > wa.json
```

### 2.4 Vhost brute-forcing — ffuf (critical on internal)

Internal reverse proxies (nginx, Apache, Traefik, IIS ARR, k8s nginx-ingress) silently front dozens of vhosts on a single IP. DNS alone won't reveal them.

```bash
ffuf -w /opt/wordlists/SecLists/Discovery/DNS/subdomains-top1million-110000.txt \
     -u https://10.10.5.20/ -H "Host: FUZZ.corp.internal" \
     -ac -mc all -fc 404 -k -t 40 -o vhosts.json -of json

# Permutation clusterbomb: FUZZ.FUZZ2
ffuf -w prefixes.txt:FUZZ -w services.txt:FUZZ2 \
     -u https://10.10.5.20/ -H "Host: FUZZ.FUZZ2.corp.internal" \
     -mode clusterbomb -ac -k
```

Some reverse proxies require SNI matching the Host header — use an `/etc/hosts` entry (`10.10.5.20 jenkins.corp.internal`) and point ffuf at the hostname directly.

### 2.5 Favicon-hash offline lookup

Many internal apps ship distinctive default favicons (Jenkins butler, GitLab tanuki, Grafana orange, Jira/Confluence blue, Gitea, Spring Boot Whitelabel, pfSense, Zabbix, vCenter, Kubernetes Dashboard, phpMyAdmin). Hashing `/favicon.ico` and matching against a known offline table instantly IDs apps even when login pages are re-branded.

```bash
httpx -l live.txt -favicon -json -duc | \
   jq -r 'select(.favicon!=null)|[.url,.favicon,.favicon_path]|@tsv' > favicons.tsv

# Match against your pre-staged hashes.tsv (hash <TAB> appname)
awk -F'\t' 'NR==FNR{m[$1]=$2;next} m[$2]{print $1"\t"m[$2]}' hashes.tsv favicons.tsv
```

Curate your hash table from `FavFreak/favicons.json` and similar repos pre-engagement.

### 2.6 cewl — build target-specific wordlists

```bash
cewl -d 3 -m 6 --lowercase --with-numbers -e -a \
     -w cewl-corp.txt --email_file emails.txt https://intranet.corp.internal/
hashcat --stdout cewl-corp.txt -r /usr/share/hashcat/rules/best64.rule > spray.txt
```

Internal product names, project codenames, team abbreviations from intranet wikis make dramatically better password-spray lists and enriched content/vhost wordlists than generic SecLists files.

