## Part 3 — Phase 3: Content and endpoint discovery

### 3.1 ffuf — the Swiss army

```bash
# Quickhits FIRST on every new app
ffuf -w /opt/wordlists/SecLists/Discovery/Web-Content/quickhits.txt \
     -u https://app.corp.internal/FUZZ -mc all -fc 404 -ac -k

# Directory brute with extensions
ffuf -w /opt/wordlists/SecLists/Discovery/Web-Content/raft-large-directories.txt \
     -u https://app.corp.internal/FUZZ \
     -e .php,.asp,.aspx,.jsp,.jspx,.do,.action,.bak,.old,.conf,.zip,.tar.gz,.txt,.xml,.json \
     -mc 200,204,301,302,307,401,403,405,500 -t 40 -timeout 10 -k -o dirs.json -of json

# Recursive
ffuf -w raft-medium-directories.txt -u https://app.corp.internal/FUZZ \
     -recursion -recursion-depth 3 -mc 200,301,302,401,403 -k

# Authenticated (cookie or bearer)
ffuf -w raft-large-directories.txt -u https://app.corp.internal/FUZZ \
     -b "JSESSIONID=AC8F9E...; XSRF-TOKEN=..." \
     -H "Authorization: Bearer eyJ..." -mc all -fc 404 -ac -k

# Parameter fuzzing
ffuf -w /opt/wordlists/SecLists/Discovery/Web-Content/burp-parameter-names.txt \
     -u 'https://app.corp.internal/search?FUZZ=test' -fs 1337 -mc all -k
```

Filter reference: `-mc`/`-fc` codes, `-ms`/`-fs` size, `-mw`/`-fw` words, `-ml`/`-fl` lines, `-mr`/`-fr` body regex, `-ac` auto-calibrate.

### 3.2 feroxbuster — recursive + link-extraction

```bash
feroxbuster -u https://app.corp.internal \
    -w /opt/wordlists/SecLists/Discovery/Web-Content/raft-medium-directories.txt \
    -x php,asp,aspx,jsp,jspx,do,action,html,bak,old,zip,conf,xml,json \
    -C 404,400 --depth 3 -k --extract-links -t 50 --auto-tune --auto-bail -o ferox.txt

# Burp shortcut
feroxbuster -u https://app.corp.internal -w common.txt --burp

# With corp CA instead of -k
feroxbuster -u https://app.corp.internal -w common.txt \
    --server-certs /etc/ssl/certs/corp-root-ca.pem
```

Feroxbuster **rejects self-signed by default** — always `-k` or `--server-certs`. `--auto-bail` stops if error rate spikes (infra overload protection).

### 3.3 dirsearch, gobuster

```bash
dirsearch -u https://app.corp.internal/ -e php,asp,aspx,jsp,html,bak -t 40 --random-agent
dirsearch -u https://app.corp.internal/ -e php,asp -r -R 3 \
          --proxy http://127.0.0.1:8080 --header "Authorization: Bearer ..."

gobuster dir  -u https://app.corp.internal/ -w raft-large-directories.txt -x php,asp,aspx,jsp -k
gobuster dns  -d corp.internal -w subdomains-top1million-110000.txt -r 10.10.0.53:53
gobuster vhost -u https://10.10.5.20/ --domain corp.internal -w subdomains-top1million-110000.txt --append-domain -k
```

### 3.4 Kiterunner — API endpoint brute with contextual .kite wordlists

Internal REST APIs — microservices, Spring Boot, Express, Django REST — are a goldmine. Traditional brute hits `GET /users`, sees 405, and gives up. Kiterunner tries `GET/POST/PUT/DELETE` with realistic body shapes and handles `/users/{id}` placeholders.

```bash
kr scan live.txt -w /opt/wordlists/kiterunner/routes-large.kite \
   -x 5 -j 100 --fail-status-codes 400,401,404,403,501,502,426,411 -o kr.txt

kr scan https://api.corp.internal/ -w routes-small.kite \
   -H "Authorization: Bearer eyJ..." -H "X-Api-Key: internal-key-xyz" --fail-status-codes 404

# Replay an interesting hit through Burp
kr kb replay -w routes-large.kite "POST 500 [40,5,1] https://api.corp.internal/user/create ..." \
   --proxy http://127.0.0.1:8080
```

routes-large.kite needs ~8GB RAM; use routes-small.kite on constrained jumpboxes.

### 3.5 katana — modern crawler (replaces gau/waybackurls)

```bash
# Core: deep crawl + JS parsing + known files + auto form-fill + include query params
katana -u https://app.corp.internal -d 5 -jc -kf all -aff -iqp \
       -c 10 -p 5 -duc -silent -o katana.txt

# Headless Chrome for SPAs
katana -u https://spa.corp.internal -hl -system-chrome \
       -headless-options="--no-sandbox,--disable-gpu,--ignore-certificate-errors" \
       -d 3 -jc -ct 30m -duc

# Extract only JS for downstream analysis
katana -u https://app.corp.internal -d 3 -jc -silent -duc | \
    grep -E '\.js(\?|$)' | sort -u > js-urls.txt
```

**Never use `-passive`** (it calls Wayback/CommonCrawl/URLScan — no egress). `-system-chrome` points at locally installed Chromium; without it, katana tries to download Chrome from Google.

### 3.6 JavaScript analysis (jsluice, LinkFinder, SecretFinder, xnLinkFinder)

Workflow (air-gapped):

```bash
# 1) Enumerate JS via katana/httpx output
# 2) Mirror JS locally
mkdir -p ./js
while read u; do wget --no-check-certificate -q -P ./js "$u"; done < js-urls.txt

# 3) Run analysis offline on disk
find ./js -name '*.js' | jsluice urls -R https://app.corp.internal > endpoints.txt
find ./js -name '*.js' | jsluice secrets > secrets.jsonl

xnLinkFinder -i ./js -o xnl-links.txt -op xnl-params.txt -os xnl-secrets.json -owl xnl-wordlist.txt

for f in ./js/*.js; do python SecretFinder.py -i "$f" -o cli -e; done
```

**jsluice** is tree-sitter based — finds endpoints constructed via string-concat that regex tools miss. Custom patterns:
```bash
cat > corp-patterns.json <<'EOF'
[{"name":"CorpInternalKey","severity":"high","value":{"pattern":"corp_api_[a-zA-Z0-9]{32}"}}]
EOF
find ./js -name '*.js' | jsluice secrets -p corp-patterns.json
```

**xnLinkFinder** accepts Burp proxy-history XML exports (`-i burp-history.xml`) and emits a target-specific wordlist — gold for the rest of the engagement.

### 3.7 Parameter discovery — Arjun, x8

```bash
arjun -u https://app.corp.internal/api/search -m GET,POST,JSON,XML \
      -w /opt/wordlists/assetnote/parameters_top_1m.txt -oT arjun.txt

# x8 — Rust, faster, also does HEADER discovery
x8 -u https://app.corp.internal/api/endpoint -w params.txt
x8 -u https://app.corp.internal --headers -w /opt/wordlists/headers.txt    # finds X-Original-URL etc.
x8 -r burp-request.txt --proto https -w params.txt                          # raw Burp request
```

**Never** use Arjun's `--passive` flag — it calls Wayback/CommonCrawl/OTX and fails silently offline.

### 3.8 gau/waybackurls/waymore — NOT USABLE INTERNALLY

All query public archives with zero internal data. Replace with:

| External approach | Internal replacement |
|---|---|
| gau / waybackurls | Burp history → export XML → `xnLinkFinder -i burp.xml` |
| waymore (Common Crawl) | `katana -d 5 -jc -kf all -aff -iqp` |
| GitHub code search | **Internal Git servers!** TruffleHog against GitLab/Gitea/Bitbucket |
| Shodan favicon | httpx `-favicon` + offline hash table |

Internal git-repo scraping replaces a decade of public Wayback/GitHub-dork workflows with **better** data:

```bash
for repo in $(curl -k -H "PRIVATE-TOKEN: $TOKEN" https://gitlab.corp.internal/api/v4/projects?per_page=100 | jq -r '.[].ssh_url_to_repo'); do
  git clone "$repo"
done
trufflehog filesystem --no-verification ./cloned-repos/ > secrets.txt
gitleaks detect -s ./cloned-repos/ -f json -r gitleaks.json
```

